figgy.title: As a user, I want to be able to ingest non-catalogued items into Figgy

comments.body:
We need to talk about this in a longer form format. Maybe @cwulfman or @kelea99 can put together a meeting? According to the Archival Description in Figgy working group, all items which have a finding aid should have item-level finding aid metadata. In cases where there isn't, a data reconciliation project should be undertaken (much as was done for western americana.) You can find the report here: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1pkhMDZcumPWgfSBiFzkTzaEVpuvwTMJMHuzW-UoDrCc/edit

As a historical note, we've put a lot of effort into trying to not turn Figgy into a cataloguing system, largely because good ones exist already and the danger is that we'd just make a bad one that doesn't reflect the training and expertise of our cataloguers. This has shown to be true with some metadata being entered into Ephemera, for instance.
@tpendragon , sure. Ill schedule something for us. this is a helpful document, thank you

marc_liberation.title: Move all the ALLOW Hathi items to 856 links in their associated record.
Load 'allow' items from full hathi report into HathiAccess
Dump all Columbia ETAS Allow/Deny into a table.

comments.body:
Can we not require that the OCLC number be unique?

The data has multiple rows with the same oclc number. In the first case I see one row is "allow" and one is "deny". I'm not sure how this is possible, but it's there and I'd need to associate the status with the bibid in order to keep them straight. But then, at some point if we load more files we'll have more rows with the same oclc number. At that point we would need to make the bibid a more complex object as opposed to just being an id, since it would need to have the source as part of that object.

Impact on https://github.com/pulibrary/marc_liberation/issues/758 is that it would return multi-item arrays.
My guess is that in serials, there are some volumes that are public domain and some that are in copyright. Are there any items identified as monographs that have this issue?
@mzelesky The one I saw was a serial. Should we not load serials?

I don't think so, but it's just another edge case. Perhaps we can surface the URL while still blocking other access, since some issues at least are available online. I'd want us to try accessing a couple records where 'allow' and 'deny' are both on the same record.
